      "title": "The God Who Specified Exactly How to Come Near",
      "hook": "Leviticus opens with God speaking from inside the tabernacle — not from the mountain, not from a burning bush — which means something has fundamentally changed about where God lives relative to Israel.",
      "teaching": "The opening word of Leviticus in Hebrew is 'Vayikra' — 'and He called.' It is the book's title in the Hebrew Bible, and it immediately signals something different from Exodus. God is no longer calling from a mountain or a burning bush. He is calling from inside the tent of meeting — the tabernacle just completed in Exodus 40. The dwelling of God among His people, which was the goal of the entire Exodus, has been achieved. Now God speaks from within the camp, from within the sanctuary, to Moses standing at the entrance. The geography of divine communication has shifted permanently. Heaven has moved into the neighbourhood.\n\nThe burnt offering — 'olah' in Hebrew, meaning 'that which goes up' — is the first and foundational offering described in Leviticus 1. It is the only offering that is entirely consumed by fire on the altar. No portion goes to the priest, no portion is eaten by the worshipper. The entire animal ascends as smoke. This totality is the theological point: the burnt offering represents complete consecration, the giving of everything to God with no portion retained. The worshipper lays their hand on the animal's head before it is slaughtered — a gesture of identification, transferring their standing onto the animal. What happens to the animal is what should happen to the offerer; what the animal gives completely, the worshipper is declaring they owe completely.\n\nThe three tiers of burnt offering in Leviticus 1 — bull, sheep or goat, bird — are not a hierarchy of worth but a provision of access. Not everyone can afford a bull. Turtledoves and pigeons are offered by those of limited means. The acceptance language is the same regardless of the animal: 'It will be accepted on their behalf to make atonement for them.' God does not grade the offering by economic value. The wealthy bull and the poor pigeon stand on equal theological ground before the altar. Luke 2:24 will note that Mary and Joseph brought two doves at Jesus' presentation — the offering of the poor — placing the family of the incarnate Son of God at the bottom of the economic tier of the very offering system He would one day fulfil.\n\nThe grain offering in Leviticus 2 is the only bloodless offering in the system, and its ingredients carry their own theology. Fine flour, olive oil, salt, and frankincense — and specifically no yeast and no honey. Yeast causes fermentation, corruption, the spread of impurity. Salt is the opposite: a preservative, a purifier, a symbol of covenant permanence. The 'salt of the covenant' appears explicitly in verse 13 — 'season all your grain offerings with salt. Do not leave the salt of your covenant with God out of your grain offerings; add salt to all your offerings.' Every offering Israel makes is to be seasoned with covenant. Worship is not occasional or compartmentalised; it is covenanted, preserved, permanent.\n\nThe fellowship offering in Leviticus 3 — 'shelem' in Hebrew, from the same root as 'shalom' — is a peace offering, a communion meal. Unlike the burnt offering where everything goes to God, the fellowship offering is divided: the fat goes to God on the altar, a portion goes to the priest, and the worshipper and their household eat the remainder. This is a shared meal between the worshipper, the priest, and God. It is the ancient world's understanding of table fellowship extended vertically — to share food is to be in relationship, and God is at this table. The prohibition on eating blood or fat in Leviticus 3:17 — 'This is a lasting ordinance for the generations to come' — is the oldest food law in the Levitical code.",
