      "title": "The Fire That Must Never Go Out",
      "hook": "God commands that the fire on the altar must never go out — not overnight, not on a Sabbath, never — and understanding why reveals something about the nature of continuous atonement that most Christians never consider.",
      "teaching": "Leviticus 6 opens with a second set of instructions about the offerings — this time addressed not to the Israelites generally but specifically to Aaron and his sons. These are the priestly regulations: what to do with the offerings once they have been brought, how the priests are to handle the sacred elements, what portions belong to them, and how the altar is to be maintained. The repetition is not redundant — different recipients require different instructions. The congregation needs to know how to bring an offering; the priest needs to know what to do with it when it arrives.\n\nThe command about the altar fire in Leviticus 6:12-13 is one of the most arresting instructions in the book: 'The fire on the altar must be kept burning; it must not go out. Every morning the priest is to add firewood and arrange the burnt offering on the fire and burn the fat of the fellowship offerings on it. The fire must be kept burning on the altar continuously; it must not go out.' The fire was lit by God Himself in Leviticus 9:24 when Aaron offered the first sacrifices and fire came out from the presence of the Lord. That divine fire was never to be extinguished — it was to be maintained by human faithfulness, the continuous human act of adding wood to a divinely initiated flame. Grace begins; diligence sustains. The fire is the perpetual declaration that the way to God is always open, that atonement is not a seasonal event but a continuous provision.\n\nThe grain offering for priests in Leviticus 6:19-23 contains a detail that surprises most readers: the priest's own grain offering must be entirely burned — no portion of it may be eaten. This is the opposite of the ordinary Israelite's grain offering, part of which the priests eat. When a priest offers a grain offering, they receive nothing back from it. The one who benefits from others' offerings receives no personal benefit from their own. The principle embedded here is one that will run through the entire biblical theology of leadership and priesthood: those who mediate between God and the people are not exempt from full consecration — they are held to a higher standard of it.\n\nThe law of the guilt offering in Leviticus 7:1-10 establishes the priests' portions in careful detail: the hide of the burnt offering belongs to the priest who offers it, the grain offerings belong to the sons of Aaron, the fat and blood belong to God on the altar. The distribution is not arbitrary — it is a system that provides for the Levitical clergy who have no tribal land allocation. The priests eat from the altar. Their livelihood is embedded in the worship system itself, making their material welfare inseparable from Israel's continued practice of approaching God. When Israel stops worshipping, the priests go hungry. The system aligns the economic interests of the clergy with the spiritual health of the congregation.\n\nThe fellowship offering laws in Leviticus 7:11-36 introduce three subcategories: thank offerings, vow offerings, and freewill offerings. The thank offering must be eaten on the day it is offered — none may be left until morning. The vow and freewill offerings may be eaten over two days. Anything left on the third day must be burned. The urgency of the thank offering is the theological point: gratitude to God should not be deferred, hoarded, or treated as an evergreen resource. The impulse to thank God when He has acted is sacred and perishable. Delay corrupts it.",
