    "studyCard": {
      "title": "Be Holy Because I Am Holy — What That Actually Means",
      "hook": "The command 'be holy because I am holy' appears five times in Leviticus 17-22, and each time it is surrounded not by mystical instruction but by laws about farming, sex, business practices, and how you treat employees — because holiness in Leviticus is always embodied.",
      "teaching": "Leviticus 17-22 is known among scholars as the Holiness Code, and its central thesis — 'be holy because I, the Lord your God, am holy' — is the most demanding and comprehensive ethical claim in the Pentateuch. Holiness is not primarily a feeling, a ritual state, or a theological category. In Leviticus 17-22 it is a practice — expressed in what you eat, how you harvest, how you treat your employee, how you conduct business, who you sleep with, and how you speak about people behind their backs.\n\nThe blood prohibition of Leviticus 17 provides the theological foundation: life is sacred because it belongs to God. The sexual ethics of Leviticus 18 provide the covenantal boundary: Israel's body life must be different from Egypt's and Canaan's, because Israel belongs to a different God. The community ethics of Leviticus 19 — which contains the love command — provide the horizontal expression of holiness: the love of God overflows into specific, demanding practices of fairness, honesty, protection of the vulnerable, and refusal of revenge.\n\nThe priestly holiness standards of Leviticus 21-22 extend the holiness principle vertically: those whose role brings them closer to God must be more comprehensively holy. The priest's body, marriage, mourning practices, and physical condition are all brought within the scope of covenant requirements. The principle is not fairness — it is function. The mediator between God and people must embody the holiness they represent.\n\nWhat is most striking about the Holiness Code when read as a whole is how little of it is mystical and how much of it is practical. The same God who specifies the exact dimensions of the atonement cover and the precise ingredients of the incense formula also specifies that you must pay your hired worker before sunset, that you must not move your neighbour's boundary stone, and that you must stand up when an elderly person enters the room. Holiness permeates every dimension of ordinary life — or it is not holiness. It is merely religious decoration.",
      "keyVerse": "Be holy because I, the Lord your God, am holy. — Leviticus 19:2 (NIV)",
      "memoryPrompt": "In Leviticus, holiness is never just about the altar — it is about farming, wages, sex, elderly people, and business scales, because God is Lord of every dimension of life.",
      "challengeFact": "Leviticus 19:36 — 'use honest scales and honest weights' — is a commercial regulation embedded in the Holiness Code, meaning that marketplace fraud is classified by the Torah alongside idol worship and sexual immorality as a violation of the holiness required by Israel's covenant relationship with God."
    },
